 oddly with the composition of my most vigorous, most festive, andcommercially most successful novel, A Kingdom by the Sea. Its demands, thefun and the fancy of it, its intricate imagery, made up in a way for theabsence of my beloved Bel. It was also bound to reduce, though I was hardlyconscious of that, my correspondence with her (well-meant, chatty,dreadfully artificial letters which she seldom troubled to answer). Evenmore startling, of course, more incomprehensible to me, in groaningretrospe